{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a61217b3-0a89-47b4-8622-d8dacbf50914","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it installable via: dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType` must be `Exe` | Tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nSince your server uses stdio transport, it works naturally as a dotnet tool — the host (e.g., Claude Desktop) launches the command directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"436c639f-4c46-471d-80ba-93d7cb15dadc","outputTokens":519,"requestId":"F056:15C54:11B95FE:141ACBA:69F94174"},"id":"a5471771-5329-4030-8655-25ef203de5aa","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:01:49.855Z","parentId":"29ae4c98-9d71-4e27-9c1f-c1510bd49a61"}
